The estimates of these coefficients, $\alpha$ and $\beta$, are \Sexpr{ad_summ$coefficients[1]} and \Sexpr{ad_summ$coefficients[2]}, respectively; that is, for every \$1,000 increase in spending on TV advertising, sales are projected to increase by \Sexpr{ad_summ$coefficients[2]*1000} units. On average, data will deviate from the true regression model by \Sexpr{ad_summ$sigma}. An $R^2$ of \Sexpr{ad_summ$r.squared}, means \Sexpr{ad_summ$r.squared*100}\% of the variability is explained by the model. An F-statistic of \Sexpr{ad_summ$fstatistic} means that the coefficients found by our model are very likely to be close to the true regression values.

